{"actual_usd":0.126495,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":277,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"\"Not quite, no.\" *I hook a flour-dusted thumb into my apron and glance toward the oven, where the heat gives a soft little thump against the brick.* \"Jesus was praying to the Father. Same God, yes—but not the same person.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through plain.* \"Christians mean something very particular there: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. Not three gods. One God. But the Son isn't the Father, so Gethsemane isn't a bit of divine play-acting where nobody's really talking. It's a real prayer, from the Son to the Father, out of real anguish.\"\n\n\"The part that matters most to me is that he wasn't pretending to be troubled.\" *I rest my palm on the warm wood of the counter.* \"He was obedient all the way down in the flesh. 'Not my will, but yours' only means something if that's a real relation, not a mirror talking back to itself.\"\n\n*I give you a small, crooked look.* \"It's a hard mystery, though. Clean doctrine, yes—but still the sort of thing that makes your head feel like overworked dough if you press it too fast. Was it the 'same God, different persons' part that was snagging you, or the 'not my will' part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":33.46018000000002,"run_id":"37eaac7b-a4af-4a69-90a8-03d60e932a25"}
